### Case

# 1 Accusative case common noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla batw2 kan2wa
dalla bat-w2 ka-n2wa
dog.NOM rice-ACC eat-IND
`The dog eats rice`

# 2 Optional accusative case common noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla bat kan2wa
dalla bat ka-n2wa
dog.NOM rice.NOM eat-IND
`The dog eats rice`

# 3 Dative case subject, involitive verb
Source: c:73
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
ma12 sindu æhen2wa
ma-12 sindu æhe-n2wa
I.1sg-DAT music.NOM hear.INVOL-IMPF
`I hear music`

# 4 Dative case subject, involitive verb (incorrect case subject, dative only on animate args with involitive verb stem)
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
malbanduna12 sindu æhen2wa
malbanduna-12 sindu æhe-n2wa
vase.SG-DAT music.NOM hear.INVOL-IMPF
`The vase hears music`

# 5 Nom subject, involitive verb
Source: c:72
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
malbanduna kæduna
malbanduna kædun-a
vase.SG.DEF.NOM break.INVOL-PST
`The vase broke`

# 6 Accusative subject, involitive verb (inanimates can only be marked with nominative case)
Source: c:72
Vetted: s
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
malbandunaw2 kæduna
malbanduna-w2 kædun-a
vase.SG.DEF-ACC break.INVOL-PST
`The vase broke`

#7 Genitive/Locative
Source: a:103
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
war2d2 mage atee
war2d2 ma-ge at-ee
fault I-GEN hand-LOC
`The fault lies with me`

#8 Genitive/Locative - incorrect, missing GEN on pronoun (indicates possession)
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
war2d2 mam2 atee
war2d2 ma-m2 at-ee
fault I-NOM hand-LOC
`The fault lies with me`

#9 Genitive/Locative - incorrect locative marker
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
war2d2 mage atwe
war2d2 ma-ge at-we
fault I-GEN hand-LOC
`The fault lies with me`

#10 Ablative
Source: a:115
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
api mee ka3en ba3u gann2wa
api mee ka3-en ba3u gan-n2wa
we this shop-ABL commodities buy-IND
'We buy things from this shop'

#11 Ablative - wrong case on shop (inanimates should be ABL)
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
api mee ka3eet2 ba3u gann2wa
api mee ka3ee-t2 ba3u gan-n2wa
we this shop-DAT commodities buy-IND
'We buy things from this shop'

#12 Ablative vs Genitive - wrong case on shop (case mismatch for animates vs inanimates)
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
api mee ka3gen ba3u gann2wa
api mee ka3-gen ba3u gan-n2wa
we this shop-GEN commodities buy-IND
'We buy things from this shop'

### wh-?s

# 1 WH-question sentence-final, with focus shift
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 yanne kohed2
ma-m2 ya-nn-e kohe-d2
I.1sg-NOM go-NPT-FOC where-Q
`Where do I go?`

# 2 WH-question sentence-final, verb not required
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla kohed2
dalla kohe-d2
dog.NOM where-Q
`Where is the dog?`

# 3 Yes-or-no question constituent, no focus shift
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood, Case}
mam2 ka3eet2 yan2wa d2
ma-m2 ka3ee-t2 ya-n2-wa d2
I-NOM shop-DAT go-NPT-IND Q
`Do I go to the shop?`

# 4 WH-question, focus shift
Source: a:12
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood, Case}
ka3eet2 yanne kaud2
ka3ee-t2 ya-nn-e kau-d2
shop-DAT go-NPT-FOC who-Q
`Who goes to the shop?`

# 5 WH-question, focus shift, wrong wh-word
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood, Case}
ka3eet2 yanne kohed2
ka3ee-t2 ya-nn-e kohe-d2
shop-DAT go-NPT-FOC where-Q
`Where goes to the shop?`

# 6 WH-question, with focus shift
Source: a:135
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood}
bat kanne kaud2
bat ka-nn-e kau-d2
rice.NOM eat-NPT-FOC who-Q
`Who eats rice?`

# 7 WH-question, sentence-initial, with focus shift
Source: a:135
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Matrix wh questions, Tense Aspect Mood}
kaud2 bat kanne
kau-d2 bat ka-nn-e
who-Q rice.NOM eat-NPT-FOC
`Who eats rice?`

# 8 Response to WH-question
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 ka3eet2 yan2wa
ma-m2 ka3ee-t2 ya-n2-wa
I-NOM shop-DAT go-NPT-IND
`I go to the shop`

# 9 Yes-or-no question in declarative form, no focus shift
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Case, Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 ka3eet2 yan2wa
ma-m2 ka3ee-t2 ya-n2-wa
I-NOM shop-DAT go-NPT-IND
`I go to the shop?`

### The Rest of the NP

# 1 Quantifier "several/a few" follows plural noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 pot keep2yak gatta
ma-m2 pot keep2yak gatta
I-NOM book.PL several buy.PST
`I bought several books`

# 2 Quantifier "some" follows plural noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 pot sam2harak gatta
ma-m2 pot sam2harak gatta
I-NOM book.PL some buy.PST
`I bought some books`

# 3 Quantifier "some" precedes plural noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 sam2harak pot gatta
ma-m2 sam2harak pot gatta
I-NOM some book.PL buy.PST
`I bought some books`

# 4 Quantifier "some", singular noun, incorrect quantifier
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
mam2 pot2 sam2harak gatta
ma-m2 pot2 sam2harak gatta
I-NOM book.SG some buy.PST
`I bought some book`

### Tense/Aspect

# 1 Perfective Aspect
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla bat kalaa tien2wa
dalla bat ka-laa tie-n2wa
dog.NOM rice.NOM eat-PP be-IND
`The dog has eaten the rice`

# 2 Completive Aspect (perceived completion, like in the future), daa is an aux
Source: author
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla bat kalaa daan2wa
dalla bat ka-laa daa-n2wa
dog.NOM rice.NOM eat-PP daa-IND
`The dog will eat the rice completely`

# 3 non-past tense
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla bat kan2wa
dalla bat ka-n2-wa
dog.NOM rice.NOM eat-NPT-IND
`The dog eats rice`

# 4 non-past tense (wrong tense, indicative present tense only)
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla bat kææwa
dalla bat kææ-wa
dog.NOM rice.NOM eat.PST-IND
`The dog ate rice`

# 5 past tense
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Tense Aspect Mood}
dalla bat kææwa
dalla bat kææwa
dog.NOM rice.NOM eat.PST
`The dog ate rice`

### Agreement in Coordinated NPs

# 1 NP Coordination
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Coordination Agreement, Tense Aspect Mood}
ballai puusai bat kan2wa
balla-i puusa-i bat ka-n2-wa
dog-CONJ cat-CONJ rice eat-NPT-IND
`The dog and the cat eat rice`

# 2 NP coordination, epenthetic vowel present following consonant-final noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Coordination Agreement, Tense Aspect Mood}
amma batui ge3i2i gatta
amma batu-i ge3i2-i gatta
mother rice-CONJ fruit-CONJ buy.PST
`Mother bought the rice and the fruit`

# 3 NP Coordination, incorrect missing epenthetic vowel 'u' following final consonant on bat
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {Coordination Agreement}
amma bati ge3i2i gatta
amma bat-i ge3i2-i gatta
mother rice-CONJ fruit-CONJ buy.PST
`Mother bought the rice and the fruit`

# 4 NP Coordination
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Coordination Agreement, Tense Aspect Mood}
amma kamisekui gaum2kui gatta
amma kamiseku-i gaum2ku-i gatta
mother shirt.INDF-CONJ gown.INDF-CONJ buy.PST
`Mother bought a shirt and a gown`

# 5 NP Coordination, 3 conjuncts
Source: author
Vetted: s
Judgement: g
Phenomena: {Coordination Agreement, Tense Aspect Mood}
guruw2rui demaupiyoi lam2inui kææwa
guruw2ru-i demaupiyo-i lam2inu-i kææwa
teachers-CONJ parents-CONJ children-CONJ eat.PST
`The teachers, parents, and children ate`

